  "prompt": "What are some unexpected things first-time visitors to Kazakhstan notice?",
  "response": "Here are some unexpected things first-time visitors to Kazakhstan might notice:\n\n1. Diverse ethnic composition\n- Large mix of ethnic groups including Kazakhs, Russians, Uzbeks, Ukrainians, and others\n- Multicultural society with many languages spoken\n\n2. Modern infrastructure in major cities\n- Especially in Nur-Sultan (Astana) and Almaty\n- Futuristic architecture, wide boulevards, and advanced public spaces\n\n3. Traditional nomadic culture coexisting with modern life\n- Yurts and traditional crafts still present\n- People maintaining strong connections to historical nomadic practices\n\n4. Unique cuisine\n- Horse meat is a common dish\n- Traditional foods like beshbarmak and kumis (fermented mare's milk)\n\n5. Vast landscapes\n- Enormous steppes and diverse terrain\n- Extremely wide-open spaces and long distances between cities\n\n6. Blend of Soviet and contemporary influences\n- Soviet-era architecture alongside modern buildings\n- Lingering Soviet cultural elements mixed with contemporary global trends\n\n7. Affordable prices\n- Generally lower cost of living compared to Western countries\n- Inexpensive dining and transportation\n\n8. High level of hospitality\n- Strong tradition of welcoming guests\n- Generous and friendly social interactions\n\nThese observations can vary depending on individual experiences and specific regions visited.",
